				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Geithner Testifies That Government Had Right to Act to Avert A.I.G. Bankruptcy</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Aaron M. Kessler			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-08T20:59:47+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 8, 2014 4:59 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 8, 2014 4:59 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/09/business/dbpix-aig-geithner/dbpix-aig-geithner-tmagArticle.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/09/business/dbpix-aig-geithner/dbpix-aig-geithner-tmagArticle.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/09/business/dbpix-aig-geithner/dbpix-aig-geithner-tmagArticle.jpg" id="100000003165405" width="592" height="395" alt="Timothy Geithner, former Treasury secretary, testified in a lawsuit brought against the government over its bailout of A.I.G."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="395"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Timothy Geithner, former Treasury secretary, testified in a lawsuit brought against the government over its bailout of A.I.G.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Chip Somodevilla/Getty Images</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/08/geithner-at-a-i-g-trial-defends-feds-loan-to-insurer/" data-title="Geithner Testifies That Government Had Right to Act to Avert A.I.G. Bankruptcy" data-description="âThe world was so fragile and the consequences of A.I.G.âs failure were so great,&quot; Mr. Geithner testified, that &quot;I was very confident&quot; the government had the authority to step in.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="entry entry-related">
<h4>Related Links</h4>
<div class="entry-related">
<ul>
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2014/09/24/business/dealbook/aig-documents.html">Documents From the A.I.G. Trial</a></li>
</ul></div>
</p></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t21h24s" class="update">Updated, 9:24 p.m. | </span>WASHINGTON â The federal government firmly pushed back on Wednesday against the notion that its 2008 bailout of the insurance giant American International Group was beyond the powers of the countryâs central bank.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Former Treasury Secretary Timothy F. Geithner testified that after A.I.G. was unable to find private investors to help it avert bankruptcy in September 2008, and after a pair of Wall Street banks rejected a proposal from the Fed that they make a loan to A.I.G., the government had every legal authority to act.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Geithner, who was president of the New York Federal Reserve Bank at the time, said the legal requirements for allowing the central bank to step in were more than satisfied, given the situation.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe world was so fragile and the consequences of A.I.G.âs failure were so great, that I was very confident we met that test,â Mr. Geithner said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A.I.G.âs former chief executive, Maurice R. Greenberg, is suing the government, claiming that the terms of the 2008 bailout, which started at $85 billion and grew to $182 billion, were too onerous. He is seeking $40 billion in compensation for himself and other A.I.G. shareholders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">At the heart of Mr. Greenbergâs case is whether the government acted lawfully in setting the terms of A.I.G.âs loan, which included a 14 percent interest rate and an initial 80 percent equity stake in the company.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After waiting a day and a half while Mr. Geithner answered questions from Mr. Greenbergâs lawyer, David Boies, the government finally got its chance to question the high-profile witness on Wednesday and did not waste any time combating the plaintiffsâ assertions.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A Justice Department lawyer, Kenneth M. Dintzer, who had said in his opening statement that A.I.G shareholders were suffering from an oversize sense of âentitlement,â walked Mr. Geithner through the crucial period in September 2008 when Fed officials went from opposing intervention to supporting it.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Geithner said that he and others at the Fed initially felt that a private solution was preferable and were reluctant to consider a government bailout of A.I.G., both because of the risk and because of the precedent of stepping in to save a company â an insurance firm â far outside the normal banking system.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Email correspondence from Ben Bernanke, then chairman of the Federal Reserve, showed Mr. Bernankeâs hesitancy to step in. He wrote that A.I.G. was in trouble âbecause theyâre acting like an investment bankâ and that they âneeded to fix this themselves,â according to documents introduced in court. An open-ended loan to A.I.G., he wrote, could be a âbridge to nowhere.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But as the situation deteriorated, and after the collapse of Lehman Brothers, Mr. Geithner said it became clear that not only would an A.I.G. failure be much worse than he originally thought, but there was ânot sufficient willingnessâ among private sector banks to step in.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe world was burning around them,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Dintzer also questioned Mr. Geithner extensively about the interest rate the government charged A.I.G. â which Mr. Boies has described as an âextortion rateâ intended to punish the company. Mr. Geithner did not shy away from the notion that the A.I.G. rate was high compared with what the government charged Wall Street banks. In fact, he said, he intentionally wanted it that way.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A Fed loan of billions of dollars to a nonbank, Mr. Geithner said, could potentially unleash a wave of other companies coming to the Fedâs doorstep as the crisis worsened, and Fed officials wanted to send a clear warning, so as to âmitigate some of the exceptional moral hazardâ that existed.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe wanted to make the conditions tough enough that they were not viewed as attractive by firms at the time in similar circumstances,â he said.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Another major point in Mr. Greenbergâs lawsuit is whether A.I.G. was only suffering from a cash flow crisis or if it was fundamentally insolvent and, therefore, quite risky.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Geithner testified on Wednesday that he thought at the time that the government could potentially lose huge sums of money.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âI thought we were taking enormous, unprecedented risk,â he said. âThere was substantial risk that we would lose billions of dollars, if not tens of billions of dollars.â</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But looking ahead, Mr. Geithner testified, he believed that the government could eventually recover its investment, and possibly any initial losses as well.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But the assertion of multibillion dollar losses drew a scathing challenge from Mr. Boies, when given the chance to question Mr. Geithner again at the end of the day. Mr. Boies, his voice as stern as at any time during the trial, sparred with Mr. Geithner about whether he had ever mentioned the risk of losing tens of billions of dollars before.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âDid you ever tell Congress that?â he asked, then posed the same question with respect to the Government Accountability Office, Congressional Oversight Panel and the Financial Crisis Inquiry Commission, all of which took testimony from Mr. Geithner over the years.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Mr. Geithner said he could not recall if he had âput a number on itâ when interviewed by those entities.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Thursday, Mr. Geithner will return to the stand for about another hour. The action will then shift to Mr. Bernanke. The trial is taking place at the Federal Court of Claims, with Judge Thomas C. Wheeler presiding.</p>
